snippet.textDisplay:
Another beautiful composition by Shuja.. Use of instruments was spot on.. Lyrics depict the illusions of love and money into which most souls fall and surely Shuja did his best to match the greatness of legendary Ibn e Insha in this department.. And the father and son did justice to the beauty of lyrics. While Sanwal's voice was refreshing and suited the urdu lyrics giving away the truth of mean world, Attaullah sir has a husky voice and reciprocates pain perfectly. Great work by backing vocals too.
Beautiful piece of art.., kudos to Coke Studio Pakistan.. 
Keep them coming.

snippet.textDisplay:
Sounds of the soil indeed!

I could instantly relate to the rhythm and the melody used here, as many 'lokgeet' have a similar, earthy setting. Even though the lyrics are in a different language, this song took me back to the Gujarati folk I have grown up listening to.

Loved Ataullah's voice and performance. The way he sings the central line of 'Ishq pawaaiyaan zanjeera' gave me goosebumps. Sanwal is good too especially at 2:50-2:55 where he sings with such mithaas. Needless to say, the lyrics rightly point out to the fickleness of this world. This is a song that I would definitely play over and over again as it's a constant reminder as to what's really important. And that too, a musical reminder!

Sab maaya hain. Sab maaya hain. :)
